00:29:20.300 --> 00:29:22.370
I teach at the Institute
of Culinary Education.

00:29:22.370 --> 00:29:24.161
I'm the director of
beverage studies there.

00:29:24.161 --> 00:29:27.410
And also, I used to do a lot
of work with the liquor brands.

00:29:27.410 --> 00:29:30.030
I was a national
brand ambassador.

00:29:30.030 --> 00:29:31.430
And a lot of educational work.

00:29:31.430 --> 00:29:33.980
So I would give sort of
very high level talks

00:29:33.980 --> 00:29:36.590
on spirits and cocktails,
history, science,

00:29:36.590 --> 00:29:39.836
trying to engage consumers
and also bartenders.

00:29:39.836 --> 00:29:41.960
And my degree's actually
in mechanical engineering,

00:29:41.960 --> 00:29:44.249
so I would get pretty geeky
in these presentations.

00:29:44.249 --> 00:29:46.790
But I would always-- but we've
been running theater companies

00:29:46.790 --> 00:29:47.520
as well.

00:29:47.520 --> 00:29:49.739
So I was running a
company with Nicole,

00:29:49.739 --> 00:29:51.530
which is the company
that we're currently--

00:29:51.530 --> 00:29:54.140
Broadway Theater Studio,
which produces The Imbible.

00:29:54.140 --> 00:29:56.690
And we decided that
we would incorporate

00:29:56.690 --> 00:29:57.980
some elements of theater--

00:29:57.980 --> 00:30:00.560
sketches and comedy
and stuff like that--

00:30:00.560 --> 00:30:01.730
into the presentations.

00:30:01.730 --> 00:30:05.120
And people loved them because,
in these presentations,

00:30:05.120 --> 00:30:07.160
you also always get cocktails.

00:30:07.160 --> 00:30:08.660
You're not going
to go to a seminar

00:30:08.660 --> 00:30:11.510
hosted by Bacardi unless
you're getting a Bacardi drink.

00:30:11.510 --> 00:30:14.280
So the standard was always three
drinks within like a couple

00:30:14.280 --> 00:30:15.520
hours that you get.

00:30:15.520 --> 00:30:20.604
And after one of these, called
The Science of Mixology,

00:30:20.604 --> 00:30:23.270
someone came up to me afterwards
and said, you live in New York.

00:30:23.270 --> 00:30:26.120
If you did this exact
presentation downtown

00:30:26.120 --> 00:30:28.610
on a Friday night,
I would go see it.

00:30:28.610 --> 00:30:32.090
So fast forward five
years or something

00:30:32.090 --> 00:30:36.470
like that, Nicole, who's an
incredibly talented writer,

00:30:36.470 --> 00:30:39.830
had been writing some plays and
was entering a show in the New

00:30:39.830 --> 00:30:42.110
York Fringe Festival 2014.

00:30:42.110 --> 00:30:43.874
And I said, you know,
I have this idea.

00:30:43.874 --> 00:30:45.540
Would you mind if I
also entered a show?

00:30:45.540 --> 00:30:46.700
And she was like,
yeah, we could--

00:30:46.700 --> 00:30:47.950
one of them--
neither of them are

00:30:47.950 --> 00:30:49.250
going to get in, but whatever.

00:30:49.250 --> 00:30:50.145
Double our chances.

00:30:50.145 --> 00:30:51.770
Well, they both got
in, and we ended up

00:30:51.770 --> 00:30:54.500
producing two full length
shows in the Fringe Festival

00:30:54.500 --> 00:30:56.210
at one time.

00:30:56.210 --> 00:30:59.030
And the Imbible
got a lot of press

00:30:59.030 --> 00:31:01.760
because we served
drinks during the show.

00:31:01.760 --> 00:31:03.990
That had never been
done at Fringe.

00:31:03.990 --> 00:31:06.410
So we got encored, and then
we opened Off-Broadway shortly

00:31:06.410 --> 00:31:08.300
after that.

00:31:08.300 --> 00:31:10.400
It started, like I
said, as lectures.

00:31:10.400 --> 00:31:13.490
The idea to bring in
sort of Greek chorus

00:31:13.490 --> 00:31:18.200
and introduce music and comedy
and sketches and costumes

00:31:18.200 --> 00:31:22.590
and all of this, the majority
of that is due to Nicole.

00:31:22.590 --> 00:31:24.470
She came aboard as
the director and said,

00:31:24.470 --> 00:31:25.770
you know, I have this vision.

00:31:25.770 --> 00:31:28.440
What if you are the bartender
and there's a staff behind you

00:31:28.440 --> 00:31:31.220
that sort of all are analogous
to restaurant servers,

00:31:31.220 --> 00:31:32.780
and they can help
propel the story.

00:31:32.780 --> 00:31:34.820
And what was going
to originally just be

00:31:34.820 --> 00:31:39.670
a one man show turned into
this full musical comedy.

00:31:39.670 --> 00:31:43.040
SPEAKER: Fantastic.

00:31:43.040 --> 00:31:47.540
The acapella harmonies that
you all are doing are amazing.

00:31:47.540 --> 00:31:49.280
Like, it's not
anything else that--

00:31:49.280 --> 00:31:50.696
certainly not
anything else that's

00:31:50.696 --> 00:31:54.170
happening on Broadway
right now or near it.

00:31:54.170 --> 00:31:55.490
Did that come easily?

00:31:55.490 --> 00:31:57.950
I mean, is this your training?

